country","country","country christmas","country road","modern country rock"]},{"id":10179393,"artist_id":995,"artist_event_id":12386284,"title":"Montgomery Gentry @ Sugar Creek Casino in Hinton, OK","datetime":"2015-11-07T20:00:00","formatted_datetime":"Saturday, November 7, 2015 at 8:00PM","formatted_location":"Hinton, OK","ticket_url":null,"ticket_type":null,"ticket_status":"unavailable","on_sale_datetime":"2015-07-17T08:00:50","facebook_rsvp_url":"http://www.bandsintown.com/event/10179393?app_id=ONTOUR_1638&artist=Montgomery+Gentry&came_from=67","description":"<p><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/PXg8E0kzF1c?rel=0&amp;controls=0&amp;showinfo=0\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"\"></iframe></p>\n<p><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/qj9b3QqTOtY?rel=0&amp;controls=0&amp;showinfo=0\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"\"></iframe> <iframe src=\"https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/Cz6Lt4_IJ14?rel=0&amp;controls=0&amp;showinfo=0\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"\"></iframe></p>\n\nMontgomery Gentry's journey into the front ranks of American music has been one of the most gratifying sagas of the past decade. Their road to\ngold and platinum albums, CMA and ACM awards, a Grammy nomination and highly successful tours has been paved both with musical integrity\nand with an abiding respect for the people and the genre they represent.\n\"We've never sold out to anybody,\" says Eddie Montgomery, whose soul-stirring baritone and 19th-century outlaw look have become iconic among\ncountry's rowdier fans. \"What you see with us is what you get.\"\n\"We've always been consistent about choosing songs that deal with the working class, songs people can identify with,\" adds Troy Gentry, whose\npiercing tenor and classic good looks provide the perfect counterpoint. \"We've stayed true to that.\"\nSeldom have entertainers been identified so closely with their fans, and seldom has the respect and affection run so deep in both directions. They\nshare blue-collar outlooks; sunup-to-sundown work ethics; rootedness in God, country and family; and the ability to celebrate life and endure\nhardship. It is a relationship few other artists in the often volatile world of show business can boast.\nNow in their 10th year on the national stage, Montgomery Gentry can look back on one of country's most impressive legacies. They have released\nmore than 20 charted singles, with anthems like \"My Town\" and \"Hell Yeah\" becoming indelible parts of the honky-tonk landscape. They have hit\nthe top of the singles charts three times, with \"If You Ever Stop Loving Me,\" \"Something To Be Proud Of\" and 2007's multi-week chart-topper\n\"Lucky Man.\" And now, with the release of Back When I Knew It All, they have taken the next big step forward.\nThe CD shows them at the top of their game, something not lost on their loyal fans, who propelled the album's title cut and first single to the top of\nthe charts more quickly than any single in the duo's history. The song serves as an introduction to a CD's worth of riches. \"Roll With Me\" shows\nTroy to be one of modern country's most stirring vocalists, the way \"God Knows Who I Am\" and \"One In Every Crowd\" showcase Eddie's vocal\ntalents, his ability to move from the raucous to the sublime, and his world-class songwriting skills. \"I Pick My Parties\" keeps the rowdiness flowing\nas it teams the boys with sometime touring partner Toby Keith, and \"One Trip\" and \"It Ain't About Easy\" display Troy and Eddie's ability to impart\nserious philosophy in the guise of an entertaining country tune.\nThe album, which both regard as the quintessential Montgomery Gentry CD, got a jump-start when the duo followed their hearts to one of the\nworld's most storied recording studios.\n\"Eddie and I and [producer] Blake [Chancey] were talking about some of the history of the music we grew up on, the artists we covered in clubs\nand the places where some of our favorite records were cut,\" says Troy. \"The name that rose above the rest was Ardent Studios down in Memphis.\nSteve Earle did Copperhead Road there, ZZ Top did Tres Hombres--there's all kinds of good stuff that's come out of there. Knowing some of the\npeople we looked up to had recorded there gave us a real sense of comfort.\"\nTroy, Eddie and the studio musicians went en masse to Memphis. They visited Graceland and Beale Street together, ate meals with each other\nand, away from the distractions of Nashville, put together Back When I Knew It All in a studio with more than 70 gold and platinum albums\nrecorded by the likes of Led Zeppelin, Stevie Ray Vaughan, Bob Dylan and Sam & Dave.\n\"The day before we started recording,\" says Troy, \"we were going over the songs to decide on tempo and instrumentation. We were in a big circle\nwith acoustic guitars and our drummer, Greg Morrow, just beating on a drum case or bongos, and I really dug getting in there doing that together\nas a team. It was probably one of the coolest parts of the process, watching the song get built right there in front of you by the musicians.\"\nWorking with Blake Chancey was a chance to team up again with the man whose work had helped define them.\n\"I tell you,\" says Eddie, \"Blake's a hell of a song guy. He's just always gotten us. He came and saw us in the old days, he signed us, and he knows\nhow we ought to be. He knows how to get the energy out of us, what kind of songs work for us, and how to capture our live performance in the\nstudio.\"\nThe journey that Chancey has seen since the early days had its roots in central Kentucky. Eddie grew up in his family's band, where he and his\nbrother John Michael spent their formative years in honky-tonks, falling in love with the music of Hank Jr., Charlie Daniels, Willie, Waylon,\nHaggard, and Lynyrd Skynyrd. Influenced by his mother's love of music, Troy favored George Jones, Haggard, Randy Travis and Hank Jr. and by\nhigh school, was in his first talent contest.\nThe Montgomery brothers and Troy joined forces in a band called Young Country until John Michael landed a record deal. His brother joined his\nband and Troy went solo, winning the national Jim Beam Talent Contest in 1994. When Eddie returned to Kentucky, he and Troy found themselves\non stage together at various charity concerts and they decided to join forces again.\n\"It just seemed like the more we were playing together around town, the bigger our following got,\" says Troy. Nashville heard the buzz, and\nColumbia Records signed them.\n1999's Tattoos and Scars announced them as a new force in country music, deeply rooted in the blue collar honky-tonk ethos that had sometimes\nbeen overlooked in the crossover success of the '90s. By their third album, 2002's My Town, they had become leaders of a movement that would\ncome to breathe new fire into country music and help bring to the forefront artists like Gretchen Wilson and Big & Rich while drawing from\nestablished artists like Hank Jr. and rockers from Lynyrd Skynyrd to Kid Rock.\nThe hits came with regularity. Eddie and Troy were named the CMA's Duo of the Year in 2000, and received that year's American Music Award for\nFavorite New Artist--Country, the Academy of Country Music Award for Top New Vocal Group or Duo, and the 2000 and 2001 Radio & Records\nReaders' Poll award for Top Country Duo. The duo performed for well over a million fans, both as headliners and as part of Kenny Chesney's \"No\nShoes, No Shirt, No Problems\" tours in 2002 and 2003, and the Brooks & Dunn \"Neon Circus & Wild West Show\" in 2001.\nTheir place as honky-tonk ambassadors has long since been established. They were part of the Rolling Stone 40th anniversary issue, they are\nintegral parts of Farm Aid and Country in the Rockies, and they joined forces with Maya Angelou after the release of \"Some People Change.\"\nTheir humanitarian efforts are another example of that place where life, art and community come together in a meaningful way.\n\"Our charitable work hit really close to home last year with the passing of my mom from cancer,\" says Troy of their work with the T. J. Martell\nFoundation, which funds cancer and AIDS research and on whose board both serve. Troy is also deeply involved in the Make-A-Wish Foundation,\nand Eddie works with Camp Horsin' Around, a camp for chronically and terminally ill children, which provides recreation and medical attention.\nTheir desire to help make the lives of others better is reflected in their desire to live their own lives fully.","artists":[{"id":995,"name":"Montgomery
